        <article class="spantwo">
          <p class="drop-cap">Recognise the student whose focus is elsewhere?
            Other interests hold their attention, rather than what is said in
            the immediate lecture or lesson? Digital technologies are often seen
            as a mechanism for content delivery. We assume students are
            receptive vessels They can be much more. You can link what you are
            teaching about to your students immediate circumstances. You can
            create connections beyond your classroom walls. Teachers can use
            technology to listen and involve their students in a learning
            experiences that extends beyond the confines of the pages in a
            textbook. </p>
          <p><strong>Do you see digital as a delivery mechanism. Or as a trigger
              or a lever that can prompt and support meaningful conversations
              and purposeful interactions?&nbsp; </strong></p>
          <p>Teaching approaches such as inquiry-based learning (IBL), mastery
            learning or authentic learning can be enabled with technology. This
            can be much more than an information dump.&nbsp; </p>
          <h4>“Content tyranny”</h4>
          <p>When the need to complete the curriculum receives the higher
            priority than dialogue, care or shared meaning making, then its
            easier to value tools, apps and devices above students well being.
            We forget the underlying values of the subject and the tools become
            the hidden curriculum.&nbsp; </p>
          <br>
        </article>
