      <h2>To Begin: Engagement and Cognition </h2>
      <p>The use of technology in the class is encouraged. But how exactly, is
        technology being positioned. Who decides how, where or what we teach.
        When tech is used with student well-being in mind, then technology can
        help students.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="strategies-engaged-get.html">Getting students engaged</a>:
          Student's complete attention is necessary for learning. Here are two
          strategies to trigger students’ initial cognitive processes. </li>
        <li><a href="strategies-engaged-maintain.html"> Maintaining Engagement</a>:
          During course activities, focused attention can be effected with clear
          structures, action based guidelines, challenging tasks and timely
          feedback. </li>
        <li><a href="strategies-engaged-re-engage.html">Re-engaging students </a>:
          A proportion of students will delay or fail to engage at key points
          during a course. Re-capturing their attention is possible with these
          two strategies; monitoring and personal attention.</li>
      </ul>
      <h2>To Consider: Flipped Learning </h2>
      <p>The flipped classroom describes a logistical arrangement. It's about
        the how and when introductory information is processed by students. And
        then what is scheduled to take place in class. Flipped learning is about
        inverting the expectations around the traditional lecture.</p>
      <ul>
        <li> <a href="strategies-flipped.html">Flipped learning</a>: Flipping
          isn’t about lessons and homework. It's about helping students to
          unpack their understanding with dynamic and interactive group
          learning. At home and in the class. </li>
      </ul>
      <h2>To Try: Backward Design</h2>
      <p>One way to challenge the content centered approach to curriculum design
        is to work backwards. This approach, known as backward design,
        prioritizes learning outcomes and meaningful assessment tasks. When you
        design backwards, you support contextualized teaching approaches. You
        guide students towards understanding. In backwards design, students can
        “show what they know” and digital scaffolding can help them “come to
        know”.</p>
      <p>Backwards designs asks lecturers to think about the END first, about
        the purpose of the course, not the content that needs to be covered. Its
        focus is on what a student should be able to accomplish, and what plans
        can be made to assist the students attain these accomplishments .</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="strategies-backwards.html">Backward design</a>:There are
          lecturers who begin their curriculum planning with the textbook.
          Backwards design advocates for the reverse. To first identify the
          desired results, then decide what constitutes acceptable evidence and
          finally plan the learning experience.</li>
      </ul>
